items.description:
WHAT IS A BIOBLITZ?
While traditional bioblitzes typically involve biologists/experts in each taxonomic field (botanists, ornithologists, herpetologists, oligochaetologists?) making collections of each plant or animal to submit to museums or herbaria over a 24 hour period, ours will be more informal. No formal training is required, and no collections will be made. We will be using the website/smartphone app iNaturalist (www.inaturalist.org) to document each individual we find. Can't identify something? Don't worry! We and the iNaturalist community at large will help with any unknown identifications. 

If you have a smartphone, great! Download the iNaturalist app (for both Android & iPhone), make an account, and try it out beforehand. If you don't have a smartphone, don't worry. You can report observations using the website directly, by uploading photos and pinpointing on a map where you observed the individual. I actually prefer this method since my phone doesn't take very good photos.

DATE & TIME:
Saturday, September 14th
9AM - 4PM

If you can't make it out in the morning, feel free to drop by for lunch at noon and afternoon bioblitzing.

LUNCH:
We will have a potluck lunch at noon, so bring something to share.

Hey Habitat 2030 Volunteers!
Almost 9 years ago, a few tree-hugging, Chicago-dwelling, twenty/thirtysomethings like ourselves hatched a crazy idea: build a community of young men and women interested in exploring, celebrating, and protecting globally-imperiled local nature. Acutely aware of Homo Sapiens var. Twentysomethingus’s propensity to stay up late on Friday, melt in the presence of Saturday morning sunlight, and congregate with other twentysomethings for good cheer and beer, these wise young adults declared, “No Habitat 2030 event shall take place before noon on a Saturday. Anyone proposing such an event shall be required to sing a Nickelback song at the next get together.”

For those of you who enjoy the soul-crushing sound of a Saturday morning alarm or Daniel’s rendition of “How You Remind Me,” we give you Saturday Morning Breakfast Cereal, a science-y webcomic we think you’ll enjoy. For some of us, reading SMBC is as close as we get to being active on an actual Saturday morning.

Fellow Chordeiles minors -- er, Nighthawks -- please join us in celebrating the return of the PM workday and the intensity of a prairie in late summer as we return to Indian Road Woods Forest Preserve on Saturday, August 31st for an afternoon of exploring, prairie resto, and conversation! Plan to stuck around after the workday for a grill-out and potluck! 

As always, bring a friend. Bring some grub. Better yet: bring a friend who brings some grub. Fermented beverages are welcome, but no glass containers, please. The FPDCC doesn’t allow it, and we’re not really that classy anyway.

This event will run from noon until 3 PM, with the potluck to follow.

If you can let us know if you’re thinking of coming, that’d be great, but last-minute drop-ins are always welcome! Details/ directions below.


Finally, here's a quick peek at a few of the Habitat 2030 events on-deck for later this summer/fall:

Look for more information about these -- and more events -- in the near future!


Cheers,
The Habitat 2030 Team

Find us on Facebook! Just search for “Habitat 2030.”

Join us on Chicago's lakefront for a dune habitat workday and bbq/swimming! 

Montrose Beach Dunes were restored (or actually rediscovered) in the 1990s when several native dune species were discovered. The City of Chicago stopped grooming the area, resulting in the formation of ridges, swales, and a large dune along the beach. Starting in 2001, high-quality native species were planted on-site to supplement the remnant vegetation that was starting to thrive. Now, it is home to rare migrating shorebirds, and an important rest stop for other migrating species. 

Help Habitat 2030 keep this vibrant and unique ecosystem healthy for all of its inhabitants. We will be primarily weeding invasive species, watering young black oaks and jack pines if conditions are hot and dry, removing trash, and repairing fences and caging around sensitive plants. Habitat tours will be offered for anyone interested! Binoculars are strongly encouraged as many resident and migratory shorebirds will be around. 

Unlike other workdays, when you get all sweaty and can only refresh yourself by drinking water, this workday will allow us the chance to swim in it! We will be BBQing (please bring anything to grill or share) and swimming until whenever we feel like. Come and go as you please. Please tell anyone and everyone you know!


Directions and parking instructions for Montrose Beach Dunes: 

The dunes are located at the far east end of Montrose Beach in Cook County. If driving, take Lake Shore Drive and exit at Montrose Avenue. Travel east along the harbor as the road winds to the right. There you will see a flagpole next to a beach house and wide beach. As you approach the beach, facing the lake, the dune habitat is to your right, between the concrete fishing pier and the handicapped ramp that divides the beach. It is the only vegetated portion of Montrose Beach. Bicycle riders, there is a lockup at the beach house. 
For public parking, park anywhere you can find space along the curb. 
For reserved parking, when arriving at Montrose by car, enter the recreational area at Montrose Avenue and Lake Shore Drive. Tell the Traffic Management Authority personnel (TMA) stationed there that you are attending a dune stewardship workday. They will let you in no matter how crowded Montrose is. If you have any problems gaining entry to the recreational area call Park District Security at 312-747-2193 and they will ensure your entry. Proceed east to the dunes and obtain a free parking pass from us (a designated volunteer will have the folder of passes). Place this on your dashboard and you park for free. The 25 spaces will not be in a specific block inside the parking lot; so you can park wherever you find a space.

Have any questions? Email us at habitat2030@gmail.com, let us know on the Habitat 2030 Facebook page, or call Daniel Suarez at (773) 415-3197 with any questions.

items.description:

Have you given any thought to what you will give your loved one on Valentine’s Day? Will it be the same-old jewel-encrusted Cadillac Escalade that you gave them last year? Or the handful of Yanni cassette tapes you bought at the gas station the year before? Or that not-so-romantic February balloon ride/haircut?

This year, maybe it’s time to think outside the box. Consider giving your schmoopy* a 3700-acre wooded estate in northwest Cook County, called Busse Woods. You could drive them down a lovely wooded lane, and get out and say “Let’s join those people with saws and loppers, and cut some brush.”

And your mate would swoon, knowing that you are both going to do the hottest thing you’ve ever done together: restore biodiversity.

Afterwards, you would enjoy chili (provided by the site steward) and then dip things in a big pot of liquid chocolate. You would tell your lover, “The French pronounce it fondue,” and she would swoon for a second time.

If you think this would make a good pre-Valentine’s Day gift, come join us!

If you can let us know if you’re thinking of coming, that will help us figure out how many tools, as well as how much chocolate fondue, to bring.

Cheers,
The Habitat 2030 Team

*or whatever you call him or her. Here are some suggestions: cabbage toes, honey bonnet, bologna noggin, love Schnauzer.

Watersmeet has a wide variety of communities, from a limey, wet woods with unusual species such as skunk cabbage, marsh marigold, dog violet and fen goldenrod to open prairie shrubland with mountain blue-eyed grass, golden sedge, and willow aster. Don't miss this opportunity to be outside in the peak of autumn color and catch up with other twenty/thirty-somethings interested in saving globally-imperiled local nature. items.summary: Midwest Ecological Prescribed Fire Training (Session 2, day 1)
items.description:
Prescribed fire is arguably the most important tool we have as we work to restore degraded ecosystems. Accordingly, Chicago Wilderness offers training sessions each year to educate volunteers interested in prescribed fire and to grow the number of trained burn crew members. Below is some information about the next opportunities!
DON'T miss this opportunity to learn about the role of prescribed fire and earn the credentials you need to be on a burn crew in this region!

Chicago Wilderness is pleased to offer the following spring sessions of the Midwest Ecological Prescription Burn Crew Member Training class. Based on the National Wildfire Coordinating Group's (NWCG) S-130 and S-190 courses, this training covers the basics of such topics as fire behavior, controlled burn techniques, and smoke management. The objective is to provide participants with the background necessary to safely participate on the crew of a controlled burn. Please be aware that although the training is accepted by many of the natural resource management agencies in the CW region as the minimum training required for a participant on a burn crew, it does not carry the official NWCG certification.

Thursday & Friday, March 13 - 14, 2014, 8am-3pm both days @ the Brookfield Zoo, Brookfield, IL
Saturday & Sunday, March 15 - 16, 2014, 8am-3pm both days @ Forest Preserve District of Cook County's Little Red Schoolhouse Nature Center, Willow Springs, IL
Saturday & Sunday, March 15 – 16, 2014, 8am-3pm both days @ Lake Bluff, IL

Registration fees will be used to help offset the cost of the trainings. The third session is sponsored in part by Lake Bluff Open Lands Association. Additional support for all trainings is provided through the in-kind contributions of CW member organizations and other partners, including the Brookfield Zoo, the Forest Preserve District of Cook County, the Forest Preserve District of DuPage County, Lake Bluff Open Lands Association, and Lake Bluff Park District.

Their status as important centers of biodiversity was earned; it has taken close to 40 years of intensive restoration work to make these areas what they are, and the work is not done yet. 

On Sunday, May 18th, we will begin the next chapter of restoration at Somme: Somme East. This area encompasses the eastern portion of Somme Woods, where restoration has been underway for quite some time. Due to the immensity of Somme Woods (over 200 acres), Somme East has not gotten the restoration attention it deserves, but Habitat 2030 can change that. 

Join us for an exploratory hike around Somme East. Led by Stephen Packard, steward at Somme Prairie Grove and Habitat 2030 mentor, we'll discover the ecosystems of Somme East, and meet the plants and animals that call this place home. Massive oaks, flying squirrels, and rare plants will be found, and there are sure to be other surprises!

Restoration work will begin at Somme East in the fall. We need to really get to know this place if we want the restoration to be effective. We'll spend a lot of time discussing the challenges facing Somme East, and how best Habitat 2030 can contribute to create as much habitat for plants and animals as quickly as possible. Don't have any experience with restoration but are eager to learn? This is a perfect opportunity to explore the concept of ecological restoration and how this important work gets accomplished. items.description:
Ever seen that Totem Pole in Chicago by the Lakefront Bike Path? Ever look PAST it? Well, read on...

All of our natural areas are unique, and have a character of their own. Bill Jarvis Migratory Bird Sanctuary is no exception. It is a 7+ acre site on the lakefront, owned by the Chicago Park District, and completely surrounded by an 8-foot tall fence. As you can imagine, this helps preserve some of the plant diversity, and gives those birds a place to rest. There are a couple of pond areas, with hand-built gravel bridges, newly-opened-up savanna areas, and a nice shed to get out of the sun.

Projects will include: 
-light brush cutting 
-garlic mustard and Japanese hedge parsley removal 
-invasive cattail and yellow iris removal

Garlic Mustard's little white flowers are starting to whither, and seed pods are already forming. Each day that passes, Garlic Mustard become harder and harder to find in a sea of green. Time for another workday at Jarvis! Bill Jarvis Migratory Bird Sanctuary is a 7+ acre Chicago Park District site on the lakefront at Addison. I used to stop during my bike ride and rest in front of that totem pole, and had no idea such an awesome place was 100 feet away.

One really good (and unique) thing about Jarvis is that there is an 8-foot fence around the whole site. This keeps out people except when there is a volunteer workday. So this is a good chance to get in there and look around. We'll probably be cutting brush and maybe an ash or two. They've been trying to open the canopy more, which has only helped their remarkable plant diversity. We'll go back in summer again to see the fruits of everyone's labor.

They also have a shed to warm up in and pretty awesome refreshments. Their workdays run from 9-2-ish, but I picked 10-1 for the official time. That gives plenty of time for those of us going to the Winter Summit at night to get ready...

Here's something different: A tree planting workday in a Chicago Park District park, and on a weekday morning! This time we're helping out Treekeepers, a program created by Openlands more than 20 years ago to help plant and take care of urban trees, both in parks and on parkways. We will plant, mulch, and water trees in this park centrally located on the north side on Irving Park Rd. between I-90/94 and Elston Ave.

Just bring some water (for you, not the trees!), and all supplies and instruction will be provided. It's about 2 blocks east of I-90/94 and 2 blocks west of Elston Ave. if you're driving. If you're taking public transportation, you can get off the Blue Line L stop at Irving and walk 3 blocks east, or take the Irving Bus (#80), which stops right in front of Independence Park.

Treekeepers was founded in 1991 as one of the first urban treekeeping programs in the country. It's an 8-week course where they bring in experts to teach everything from planting, pruning, and mulching to benefits of trees for people and communities to tree ID to pests and diseases, etc. Over 1500 Treekeepers have taken the course, and they planted over 1000 trees last year, mostly in Chicago. They usually have classes on the north side in Fall and the south side in Spring, plus the Morton Arboretum and Ryerson Woods. They are starting to 'branch' out, and are planning to offer classes in Lake, DuPage, and several southern Chicago counties. And certified Treekeepers are allowed to prune, mulch, and water trees in parks and parkways in the city of Chicago (with a little advance notice).

Join us this Friday from 4:30 to 7:30 to collect Prickly Ash Seeds at Bunker Hill preserve.

Several experienced stewards and naturalists including John and Jane Balaban, Eileen Sutter and Michael Swierz will lead us to the prickly ash seeds, and most certainly let us in on some of their best tidbits about this incredible preserve. 

Wear long pants as we may walk through brush, and bring plenty of bug spray and water. Meet at the Bunker Hill Parking Lot and if you're late, text or call 512-431-6016. Contact Cecil Hynds-Riddle at cecilhyndsriddle@gmail.com if you need to carpool from the city.

Chicago is home to several dunes, and they only have warm-weather workdays, so we're trying to fit them all in! Don't make the mistake of thinking they are all the same, though. They have a lot of similarities, but they all have their own character...

There is a park south of Touhy in Chicago called Loyola Park, and this dunes is, therefore, called Loyola Park Dunes -- not associated with the university, although some students help out from time to time. Inevitably, Loyola Dunes gets compared to Montrose Dunes, but they are both different and unique. Loyola is smaller, but also less busy. There is something peaceful and tranquil about it, although the same could be said about Montrose, after you get settled into a task, and many other natural areas. But I feel Loyola is a little more so, and I am always happy I went.

We'll be doing invasives removal, which means you get to play around in the sand. Just like when you were a kid! Plus the steward, Ann Whelan, will show us around, Loyola was basically a field of Sweet Clover when she started, but now it's quite diverse.

Dunes are pretty rare in Illinois, so some of the plants aren't real common other places. There are also some birds and dragonflies, damselflies, butterflies, and **MILKWEED BEETLES**! (I know, I use the same pictures over and over, but I LOVE this one...)

items.summary: LaBagh Field Trip to Somme Woods: Shooting Star Meadow Rescue!
items.description:
In the Spring of 2015, volunteers discovered a mysterious phenomenon in the Woods of Somme East. Shooting Stars burst from the earth under the thickest thicket you ever did see. As it turns out, the Shooting Star Meadow of Somme Woods East is in the middle of a prairie. It certainly doesn't look like a prairie now, with so much buckthorn marring the view, but the absence of large oaks and the presence of remnant prairie species tells us it is so. 

LaBagh volunteers will take a field trip to Somme Woods for this community event and we will save the shooting star meadow from certain doom! Huzzah! 

You may notice that this brush slaying day is a bit longer than usual. That's because we will take a nice long break in the middle for Somme and LaBagh volunteers to mingle, and we have so much to do to save these precious plants! You're encouraged to bring food to share!

Carpooling will be available from the LaBagh Woods Foster parking lot at 9am - 4498 Foster Ave, Chicago. If you have a seat to share or you'd like to hitch a ride, please email cecilhyndsriddle@gmail.com so we know to expect you. Volunteers are also invited to go straight to Somme Woods at 10am.

items.description:
We all know that Illinois is the "Prairie State". But how many of us have actually stood in a vast, expansive grassland and truly felt the sublime exaltation of the prairie?

NOW IS YOUR CHANCE

Bartel Grassland, a 1,000+ acre preserve in southern Cook County, is a rarity in our highly urbanized landscape. It has the size to support populations of rare grassland-nesting birds and to inspire awe in the minds and hearts of humans.

Only 30 minutes from downtown Chicago, Bartel is a place of great ecological importance. It is one of a handful of sites in the Chicago region that can truly give us a glimpse into the past. To stand in the middle of the Bartel prairie is to look back to a time when vast herds of bison and passenger pigeons called Chicago home. 

Habitat 2030 will be working to clear invasive brush and trees from the southern edge of the prairie. Recently, a pair of bald eagles has started building their nest nearby! Our work will ensure that many rare, imperiled species have more habitat to enjoy. 

Habitat 2030 has just recently started holding workdays in this region of the county. We KNOW there are many young, interested, and eager restorationists out there. We're relying on YOU to help spread the word and generate interest in the site. 

Meet in the abandoned strip mall parking lot on Vollmer Road: https://goo.gl/maps/fnAXkQmQjWD2

From there, we'll hike up to the worksite and get to work, sawing, lopping, laughing, and eating alongside a raging bonfire. 

As always, EXPERIENCE IS NOT REQUIRED. We are trying to develop the next generation of volunteer stewards of the land, and all are welcome!

Please bring a water bottle and weather-appropriate clothes. Gloves and tools will be provided. As always, please avoid wearing synthetic clothing, as embers from the fire can burn holes in the fibers. 

For questions the day of, contact Daniel Suarez at 773-415-3197.

items.description:
Time to do a little brush cutting in another Chicago Park District site! This one's at Clark Park, an up-and-coming park on the Chicago River.

Located on Rockwell between Addison and Belmont, it sits right behind Lane Technical High School. They built a new field house, and a brand new boat house for rowers and a new dock for canoe launching.

Openlands' Treekeepers planted 25 trees there last year, but there is too much shade from non-native trees, so we're going to help them cut out the invasives so the ones we planted can get more light. A big group of us can make a BIG dent. Then in spring we'll plant more trees!

There's plenty of parking along Rockwell, and a small parking lot. Bring water so you can stay hydrated, sturdy shoes, and layers of clothes in case you get hot...

The list of cool things about Clark Park is very long. Here's a few:

- On the Chicago River
- Has roughly 6 acres of woods, interspersed by:
- Chicago Area Mountain Bikers (CAMBr) has mountain bike trails there with ramps and jumps, right in the middle of the woods. They call it 'The Garden' on their website. It's still a work in progress, but they intend to have some small hills and jumps for all levels eventually
- The City is going to build underpasses so bicyclists can ride along the Chicago River. Eventually it will connect to the trail up north, which will eventually connect to the North Branch Trail to the Botanic Gardens
- There is a new dock for canoes/kayaks, etc. to launch from
- They have rowing clubs based in their new boat house, which includes indoor rowing facilities
- There is a new soccer field across the steet, and the a new baseball field called Kerry Woods Cubs Field, sponsored by...?

And those are just what has been built or confirmed. Let's help them get their woods healthy!

items.description:
This unique former prairie in Somme Woods East requires the ground to be frozen for us to work. Without the ground frozen we would risk "plowing" the soil and destroying the beautiful shooting stars and other rare plants. Lucky for us, there is no risk of the ground thawing before Saturday! Come help connect the shooting star meadow to the North Brook stream during this workday. This summer we will likely see hundreds of blooming shooting stars while overlooking the stream which has been obscured by buckthorn for decades. 

Wear clothes that you don't mind getting dirty. We suggest wearing wool, cotton, or other natural fibers as the bonfire can burn little hole in your fancy jackets. Speaking of that fire, feel free to bring something to cook on it at the end! Others have brought chili, s'mores, foil packs of veggies, and other things to share. Be creative!

items.summary: Restoration Case Study of Miami Woods and Prairie: a site walk and talk by Kent Fuller
items.description:
This is a unique opportunity to learn about the successes, challenges, and landmarks of a 30 year restoration endeavor at Miami Woods. Anyone is welcome to attend this workshop, but this is a particularly wonderful opportunity for budding naturalists and future stewards to ask questions, learn from decades of experience, and find out about the current needs for new stewards to continue this great work.

Our host, Kent Fuller, has been a member of the North Branch Restoration Project for 25 years. He is the co-steward, with his wife Jerry Fuller, of the 112 acre Miami Woods and Prairie. He was on the Glenview Village board of Trustees when the Naval Air Station closed and was instrumental in saving the Prairie and building the Tyner Interpretive Center. 

Workshop Schedule

2:00 - We will meet at Miami Woods parking lot for a site tour.  The parking lot is accessed off Caldwell, just north of Oakton on the east side of street. Note that currently there is no sign.

4:00 - Drive to Tyner Center, 2400 Compass Drive, Glenview

4:30 - Kent will give a brief talk about restoration in Miami Woods and the Air Station Prairie and be available for discussion. Refreshments served.

5:30 - Program concludes

With questions email Eriko Kojima: erikokojima at gmail dot com

items.summary: In the Cut: Ravines Flora Tour with Rachel Goad of Plants of Concern
items.description:
Join Habitat 2030 and Rachel Goad of Plants of Concern for a tour of the spring wildflowers of the rare Chicago Ravines system. Many unusual and unlikely plants abound in these fragile and bluffy lakeside habitats. We'll explore a couple spectacular examples of glacial ice age remnant flora in one of Illinois’s last natural drainage systems to the lake. 

OUR STARTING POINT HAS CHANGED. PLEASE RSVP BY EMAIL and Michael will provide you with the new meeting location. From there, we will travel to two or three ravines nearby to explore the spectacular spring flora that lives there. Come learn about the unique plants that live in these ecosystems and the restoration projects underway to preserve and maintain these precarious habitats.

On the way back home, we'll head over to Lake Bluff Brewing Company to enjoy some local brews of the vicinity.

To RSVP: 

Please RSVP with an email to mswierz AT gmail.com to let us know you are coming, so we can plan accordingly. Due to space constraints in the ravines and the fragile nature of the ecosystem, it is possible we may need to limit the number of attendees for this event. Should this be the case, preference will be given to whomever has RSVP'd by email first.

To learn more about the ravines: 

http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-06-25/travel/chi-brotman-090910-rareplants-story_1_ravines-lakeshore-preserve-openlands

Busse Woods is one of the biggest and most biodiverse sites in Cook County and the region. Come appreciate the diversity in the woodlands, flatwoods, prairies, and lakes of Busse, and get rid of an invasive species in the process!

Steward Erin Faulkner will show us how to hunt for signs of our animal visitors such as coyotes, skunks, rabbits, ducks, songbirds, & prairie crayfish.

items.description:
What a name for an activity! 

We will don our wellies and go deep into the Somme Woods ponds to search for salamander larvae (colloquially called "sallywogs"). This activity will delight your curiosity, but it has a very important scientific purpose. We want to find out if our salamanders are reproducing effectively and if their populations are increasing year by year. To find that out we need to look for sallywogs each spring, starting.... now! We'll do this for years to come and voila data!

We recommend wearing rain boots or waders if you have them in your wardrobe. Waterproof pants are also helpful, but of course they don't protect your socks from getting wet. 

Please do not wear sunscreen or bug spray anywhere that will contact the water. If you apply it to your face and neck (of course we recommend protecting yourself from sunburn) please wash your hands before you come so you do not get it in the water. Please also scrub down your boots to remove all mud collected from other forest preserves or your garden, then spritz them or dip them in rubbing alcohol or hydrogen peroxide. These precautions are necessary to protect this delicate ecosystem from contamination by salamander and frog killing fungi and pollutants. 

Please contact cecil hynds riddle at gmail dot com with questions.

items.summary: Inaugural H2030 Workday at Bartel Grassland!
items.description:
We all know that Illinois is the "Prairie State". But how many of us have actually stood in a vast, expansive grassland and truly felt the sublime exaltation of the prairie?

NOW IS YOUR CHANCE

Bartel Grassland, a nearly 600 acre preserve in southern Cook County, is a rarity in our highly urbanized landscape. It has the size to support populations of rare grassland-nesting birds and to inspire awe in the minds and hearts of humans.

Only 20 minutes from downtown Chicago, Bartel is a place of great ecological importance. It is one of a handful of sites in the Chicago region that can truly give us a glimpse into the past. To stand in the middle of the Bartel prairie is to look back to a time when vast herds of bison and passenger pigeons called Chicago home. 

Habitat 2030 will be working at the edge of the prairie, in the Bartel Shrubland. Shrublands are important, little-understood ecosystems that once were much more common. They provide integral habitat to many rare plants and animals. We'll be working to clear invasive brush and trees in the hopes of enhancing this precious habitat. 

Habitat 2030 has never done a workday in this part of the region. We KNOW there are many young, interested, and eager restorationists out there. We're relying on YOU to help spread the word and generate interest in the site. 

Meet in the Bartel Grassland parking lot on Flossmoor Rd.: https://goo.gl/maps/wW8TV

From there, we'll hike up to the shrubland and get to work, sawing, lopping, laughing, and eating alongside a raging bonfire. 

As always, EXPERIENCE IS NOT REQUIRED. We are trying to develop the next generation of volunteer stewards of the land, and all are welcome!

Please bring a water bottle and weather-appropriate clothes. Gloves and tools will be provided. As always, please avoid wearing synthetic clothing, as embers from the fire can burn holes in the fibers. 

For questions the day of, contact Daniel Suarez at 773-415-3197. 

If you're interested in carpooling, comment below and let's start the conversation!

items.summary: Leaf Litter: The Natural Heritage of Illinois by John Schwegman
items.description:
Welcome to Habitat 2030's new book club: "Leaf Litter." Everyone is welcome and we hope to do this once every couple months with a new book. This time we are meeting at the Flossmoor Station Restaurant & Brewery in the south suburbs (set up a carpool by commenting on this event). As we choose a new book we will also choose a new meeting locaiton so we can be geographically fair to eveyone.

Read the book. Bring questions and thoughtful comments. No pressure. Just fun.

For our first meeting we wil be reading John Schwegman's new book "The Natural Heritage of Illinois Essays on Its Lands, Waters, Flora, and Fauna"

John E. Schwegman is the principal author of The Natural Divisions of Illinois, a classification of the state’s natural lands that guides the development of the Illinois Nature Preserves System. He established the Natural Areas Program (now Division of Natural Heritage) at the Illinois’ Department of Natural Resources and since retirement has served as a commissioner of the Illinois Nature Preserves Commission. He led the founding of the Natural Areas Association, America's professional society for nature conservationists, and served as its first President. Currently, he serves as a consultant to the Illinois Nature Preserves Commission.

Habitat 2030 tie-in: John was an important figure in the 1980s and 90s when he did the first floristic survey of Langham Island. He along with others started intensive managment there to save the Kankakee Mallow. #ConservationHero Links to buy the book, read a preview, check out reviews: 
SIU press: http://siupress.com/product/Natural-Heritage-of-Illinois,6359.aspx 
Amazon: https://www.amazon.com/Natural-Heritage-Illinois-Essays-Waters/dp/0809334844

Hope to see you there!

items.summary: Leaf Litter: "Reading the Landscape of America"
items.description:
Welcome to Habitat 2030's new book club: "Leaf Litter." 

Everyone is welcome and we hope to do this once every couple months with a new book. This time we are meeting at the Daniel Suarez's apartment in Chicago's Ukrainian Village neighborhood (set up a carpool by commenting on this event). As we choose a new book we will also choose a new meeting locaiton so we can be geographically fair to everyone.

Read the book. Bring questions and thoughtful comments. No pressure. Just fun.

This time around we are reading "Reading the Landscape of America" by May Thielgaard Watts. May studied with Henry Chandler Cowles, the godfather of ecology, and she was the first to explain the theory of plant succession to the general public. May worked at the Morton Arboretum for many years as a naturalist, and led the charge to establish the Illinois Prairie Path. 

You can purchase the book here, although we do encourage you to buy from a local bookstore if possible: https://www.amazon.com/Reading-Landscape-America-Theilgaard-Watts/dp/0912550236 

In particular, we will focus on the following chapters: 

4. Picnic in a Gritty Wind, or The Sand Dunes of Indiana
5. History Book with a Flexible Cover, or The Records in a Quaking Bog
6. Prairie Plowing Match, or The Making and Breaking of the Tall Grass Sod
10. Camp Sites, Fires, and Cud-Chewers, or How the Upland Forest Changes, Illinois to Wisconsin

Bring your thoughts, something to drink and/or a snack to share!
Call Daniel at 773-415-3197 to be let in. 

Hope to see you there!
